Kubernetes

Kubernetes, often abbreviated as K8s, is an open-source container orchestration platform designed to automate the deployment, scaling, and management of containerized applications. Originally developed by Google and now maintained by the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF), Kubernetes has become the industry standard for container orchestration.
At its core, Kubernetes abstracts the underlying infrastructure—whether on-premises or cloud—and provides a unified API to manage application workloads. It groups containers into logical units called Pods, which are the smallest deployable units. Kubernetes manages Pods across clusters of machines, automatically handling scheduling, load balancing, scaling, and self-healing.
Key features include:
•	Automated rollouts and rollbacks: Kubernetes can progressively deploy changes or revert if issues arise.
•	Self-healing: It automatically restarts failed containers or replaces unhealthy nodes.
•	Horizontal scaling: Automatically adjusts the number of running instances based on demand.
•	Service discovery and load balancing: Internal networking and DNS to route requests efficiently.
•	Secret and configuration management: Securely manage sensitive information and application configuration.
By simplifying complex container lifecycle management, Kubernetes enables organizations to build reliable, scalable, and portable cloud-native applications.
